nological intervention is folded into an Andean understanding of reproduction as always assisted, whether through kin or God. She argues that the Ecuadorian incarnation of reproductive technology is less about a national desire for modernity than it is a product of colonial racial history, Catholic practice, and kinship configurations. God's Laboratory offers a grounded introduction to critical debates in medical anthropology and science studies, as well as a nuanced ethnography of the interplay between science, religion, race and history in the formation of Andean families.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aFertilization in vitro, HumanxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 0aHuman reproductive technologyxAndes Region. 0aHuman reproductive technologyxEcuador. 0aHuman reproductive technologyzAndes Region. 0aHuman reproductive technologyzEcuador. 0aMedical anthropologyxAndes RegionxAndes RegionxEcuador. 0aMedical anthropologyxEcuador. 0aMedical anthropologyzAndes Region. 0aMedical anthropologyzEcuador. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520952256423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520952256.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles